<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><entry xml:lang="en" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:planet="http://planet.intertwingly.net/"><id>http://tcsmath.org/?p=2115</id><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/2015/11/16/entropy-optimality-on-path-space/" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/><title>Entropy optimality on path space</title><summary type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">After Boaz posted on the mother of all inequalities, it seemed about the right time to get around to the next series of posts on entropy optimality. The approach is the same as before, but now we consider entropy optimality on a path space. After finding an appropriate entropy-maximizer, the Brascamp-Lieb inequality will admit a … <a class="more-link" href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/2015/11/16/entropy-optimality-on-path-space/">Continue reading <span class="screen-reader-text">Entropy optimality on path space</span></a></div><div class="commentbar"><p/></div></summary><content type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p>After Boaz posted on the <a href="http://windowsontheory.org/2015/11/08/the-mother-of-all-inequalities/">mother of all inequalities</a>, it seemed about the right time to get around to the next series of posts on entropy optimality.  The approach is the same as before, but now we consider entropy optimality on a <em>path space</em>.  After finding an appropriate entropy-maximizer, the Brascamp-Lieb inequality will admit a gorgeous one-line proof.  Our argument is taken from the <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1006.3028">beautiful paper of Lehec</a>.</p>
<p>For simplicity, we start first with an entropy optimization on a discrete path space.  Then we move on to Brownian motion.</p>
<p><b>1.1 Entropy optimality on discrete path spaces </b></p>
<p/><p>
Consider a finite state space <img alt="{\Omega} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\Omega} "/> and a transition kernel <img alt="{p : \Omega \times \Omega \rightarrow [0,1]} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp+%3A+%5COmega+%5Ctimes+%5COmega+%5Crightarrow+%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{p : \Omega \times \Omega \rightarrow [0,1]} "/>. Also fix some time <img alt="{T \geq 0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT+%5Cgeq+0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{T \geq 0} "/>.</p>
<p>
Let <img alt="{\mathcal P_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal+P_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathcal P_T} "/> denote the space of all paths <img alt="{\gamma : \{0,1,\ldots,T\} \rightarrow \Omega} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma+%3A+%5C%7B0%2C1%2C%5Cldots%2CT%5C%7D+%5Crightarrow+%5COmega%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma : \{0,1,\ldots,T\} \rightarrow \Omega} "/>. There is a natural measure <img alt="{\mu_{\mathcal P}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu_{\mathcal P}} "/> on <img alt="{\mathcal P_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal+P_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathcal P_T} "/> coming from the transition kernel: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \mu_{\mathcal P}(\gamma) = \prod_{t=0}^{T-1} p\left(\gamma(t), \gamma(t+1)\right)\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmu_%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%28%5Cgamma%29+%3D+%5Cprod_%7Bt%3D0%7D%5E%7BT-1%7D+p%5Cleft%28%5Cgamma%28t%29%2C+%5Cgamma%28t%2B1%29%5Cright%29%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \mu_{\mathcal P}(\gamma) = \prod_{t=0}^{T-1} p\left(\gamma(t), \gamma(t+1)\right)\,.  "/></p>
<p>
Now suppose we are given a starting point <img alt="{x_0 \in \Omega} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_0+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x_0 \in \Omega} "/>, and a target distribution specified by a function <img alt="{f : \Omega \rightarrow {\mathbb R}_+} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%3A+%5COmega+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cmathbb+R%7D_%2B%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f : \Omega \rightarrow {\mathbb R}_+} "/> scaled so that <img alt="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[f(X_T) \mid X_0 = x_0]=1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Bf%28X_T%29+%5Cmid+X_0+%3D+x_0%5D%3D1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[f(X_T) \mid X_0 = x_0]=1} "/>. If we let <img alt="{\nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\nu_T} "/> denote the law of <img alt="{X_T \mid X_0 = x_0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX_T+%5Cmid+X_0+%3D+x_0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{X_T \mid X_0 = x_0} "/>, then this simply says that <img alt="{f} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f} "/> is a density with respect to <img alt="{\nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\nu_T} "/>. One should think about <img alt="{\nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\nu_T} "/> as the natural law at time <img alt="{T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{T} "/> (given <img alt="{X_0=x_0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX_0%3Dx_0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{X_0=x_0} "/>), and <img alt="{f \nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f \nu_T} "/> describes a perturbation of this law.</p>
<p>
Let us finally define the set <img alt="{\mathcal M_T(f; x_0)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal+M_T%28f%3B+x_0%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathcal M_T(f; x_0)} "/> of all measures <img alt="{\mu} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu} "/> on <img alt="{\mathcal P_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal+P_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathcal P_T} "/> that start at <img alt="{x_0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x_0} "/> and end at <img alt="{f \nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f \nu_T} "/>, i.e. those measures satisfying </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \mu\left(\{\gamma : \gamma(0)=x_0\}\right) = 1\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmu%5Cleft%28%5C%7B%5Cgamma+%3A+%5Cgamma%280%29%3Dx_0%5C%7D%5Cright%29+%3D+1%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \mu\left(\{\gamma : \gamma(0)=x_0\}\right) = 1\,,  "/></p>
<p> and for every <img alt="{x \in \Omega} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x \in \Omega} "/>, </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  f(x) \nu_T(x) = \sum_{\gamma \in \mathcal P : \gamma(T)=x} \mu(\gamma)\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++f%28x%29+%5Cnu_T%28x%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7B%5Cgamma+%5Cin+%5Cmathcal+P+%3A+%5Cgamma%28T%29%3Dx%7D+%5Cmu%28%5Cgamma%29%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  f(x) \nu_T(x) = \sum_{\gamma \in \mathcal P : \gamma(T)=x} \mu(\gamma)\,.  "/></p>
<p>
Now we can consider the entropy optimization problem: <a name="eqoptimize"/></p><a name="eqoptimize">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \min \left\{ D(\mu \,\|\, \mu_{\mathcal P}) : \mu \in \mathcal M_T(f;x_0) \right\}\,. \ \ \ \ \ (1) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmin+%5Cleft%5C%7B+D%28%5Cmu+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%29+%3A+%5Cmu+%5Cin+%5Cmathcal+M_T%28f%3Bx_0%29+%5Cright%5C%7D%5C%2C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \min \left\{ D(\mu \,\|\, \mu_{\mathcal P}) : \mu \in \mathcal M_T(f;x_0) \right\}\,. \ \ \ \ \ (1) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqoptimize"/> One should verify that, like many times before, we are minimizing the relative entropy over a polytope. </p>
<p>
One can think of the optimization as simply computing the most likely way for a mass of particles sitting at <img alt="{x_0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x_0} "/> to end up in the distribution <img alt="{f \nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f \nu_T} "/> at time <img alt="{T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BT%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{T} "/>.</p>
<p>
The optimal solution <img alt="{\mu^*} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%5E%2A%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu^*} "/> exists and is unique. Moreover, we can describe it explicitly: <img alt="{\mu^*} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%5E%2A%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu^*} "/> is given by a time-inhomogeneous Markov chain. For <img alt="{0 \leq t \leq T-1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0+%5Cleq+t+%5Cleq+T-1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{0 \leq t \leq T-1} "/>, this chain has transition kernel <a name="eqqkernel"/></p><a name="eqqkernel">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  q_t(x,y) = p(x,y) \frac{H_{T-t-1} f(y)}{H_{T-t} f(x)}\,, \ \ \ \ \ (2) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++q_t%28x%2Cy%29+%3D+p%28x%2Cy%29+%5Cfrac%7BH_%7BT-t-1%7D+f%28y%29%7D%7BH_%7BT-t%7D+f%28x%29%7D%5C%2C%2C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  q_t(x,y) = p(x,y) \frac{H_{T-t-1} f(y)}{H_{T-t} f(x)}\,, \ \ \ \ \ (2) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqqkernel"/> where <img alt="{H_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BH_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{H_t} "/> is the <em>heat semigroup</em> of our chain <img alt="{\{X_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BX_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{X_t\}} "/>, i.e. </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  H_t f(x) = \mathop{\mathbb E}[f(X_t) \mid X_0 = x]\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++H_t+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Bf%28X_t%29+%5Cmid+X_0+%3D+x%5D%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  H_t f(x) = \mathop{\mathbb E}[f(X_t) \mid X_0 = x]\,.  "/></p>
<p> Let <img alt="{\{W_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_t\}} "/> denote the time-inhomogeneous chain with transition kernels <img alt="{\{q_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bq_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{q_t\}} "/> and <img alt="{W_0=x_0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_0%3Dx_0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_0=x_0} "/> and let <img alt="{\mu} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu} "/> denote the law of the random path <img alt="{\{W_0, \ldots, W_T\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_0%2C+%5Cldots%2C+W_T%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_0, \ldots, W_T\}} "/>. We will now verify that <img alt="{\mu} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu} "/> is the optimal solution to <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqoptimize">(1)</a>.</p>
<p>
We first need to confirm that <img alt="{\mu \in \mathcal M_T(f;x_0)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu+%5Cin+%5Cmathcal+M_T%28f%3Bx_0%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu \in \mathcal M_T(f;x_0)} "/>, i.e. that <img alt="{W_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_T} "/> has law <img alt="{f \nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f \nu_T} "/>. To this end, we will verify inductively that <img alt="{W_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_t} "/> has law <img alt="{(H_{T-t} f)\cdot \nu_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28H_%7BT-t%7D+f%29%5Ccdot+%5Cnu_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{(H_{T-t} f)\cdot \nu_t} "/>. For <img alt="{t=0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt%3D0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{t=0} "/>, this follows by definition. For the inductive step: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  \displaystyle\mathop{\mathbb P}[W_{t+1}=y] &amp;= \sum_{x \in \Omega} \Pr[W_t=x] \cdot p(x,y) \frac{H_{T-t-1} f(y)}{H_{T-t} f(x)} \\ \displaystyle&amp;= \sum_{x \in \Omega} H_{T-t} f(x) \nu_t(x) p(x,y) \frac{H_{T-t-1} f(y)}{H_{T-t} f(x)} \\ \displaystyle&amp;= \sum_{x \in \Omega} \nu_t(x) p(x,y) H_{T-t-1}f(y) \\ \displaystyle &amp; = H_{T-t-1} f(y) \nu_{t+1}(y)\,. \end{array}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Blll%7D++%5Cdisplaystyle%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+P%7D%5BW_%7Bt%2B1%7D%3Dy%5D+%26%3D+%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D+%5CPr%5BW_t%3Dx%5D+%5Ccdot+p%28x%2Cy%29+%5Cfrac%7BH_%7BT-t-1%7D+f%28y%29%7D%7BH_%7BT-t%7D+f%28x%29%7D+%5C%5C+%5Cdisplaystyle%26%3D+%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D+H_%7BT-t%7D+f%28x%29+%5Cnu_t%28x%29+p%28x%2Cy%29+%5Cfrac%7BH_%7BT-t-1%7D+f%28y%29%7D%7BH_%7BT-t%7D+f%28x%29%7D+%5C%5C+%5Cdisplaystyle%26%3D+%5Csum_%7Bx+%5Cin+%5COmega%7D+%5Cnu_t%28x%29+p%28x%2Cy%29+H_%7BT-t-1%7Df%28y%29+%5C%5C+%5Cdisplaystyle+%26+%3D+H_%7BT-t-1%7D+f%28y%29+%5Cnu_%7Bt%2B1%7D%28y%29%5C%2C.+%5Cend%7Barray%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  \displaystyle\mathop{\mathbb P}[W_{t+1}=y] &amp;= \sum_{x \in \Omega} \Pr[W_t=x] \cdot p(x,y) \frac{H_{T-t-1} f(y)}{H_{T-t} f(x)} \\ \displaystyle&amp;= \sum_{x \in \Omega} H_{T-t} f(x) \nu_t(x) p(x,y) \frac{H_{T-t-1} f(y)}{H_{T-t} f(x)} \\ \displaystyle&amp;= \sum_{x \in \Omega} \nu_t(x) p(x,y) H_{T-t-1}f(y) \\ \displaystyle &amp; = H_{T-t-1} f(y) \nu_{t+1}(y)\,. \end{array}  "/></p>
<p>
We have confirmed that <img alt="{\mu \in \mathcal M_T(f;x_0)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu+%5Cin+%5Cmathcal+M_T%28f%3Bx_0%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu \in \mathcal M_T(f;x_0)} "/>. Let us now verify its optimality by writing </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(f \nu_T \,\|\,\nu_T) = \mathop{\mathbb E}_{\nu_T} [f \log f] = \mathop{\mathbb E}[\log f(W_T)]\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28f+%5Cnu_T+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C%5Cnu_T%29+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D_%7B%5Cnu_T%7D+%5Bf+%5Clog+f%5D+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5B%5Clog+f%28W_T%29%5D%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(f \nu_T \,\|\,\nu_T) = \mathop{\mathbb E}_{\nu_T} [f \log f] = \mathop{\mathbb E}[\log f(W_T)]\,,  "/></p>
<p> where the final equality uses the fact we just proved: <img alt="{W_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_T} "/> has law <img alt="{f \nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f \nu_T} "/>. Continuing, we have </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \mathop{\mathbb E}[\log f(W_T)] = \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\log \frac{H_{T-t-1} f(W_{t+1})}{H_{T-t} f(W_t)}\right] = \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \mathop{\mathbb E} \left[D(q_t(W_t, \cdot) \,\|\, p(W_t,\cdot))\right]\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5B%5Clog+f%28W_T%29%5D+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bt%3D0%7D%5E%7BT-1%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Cleft%5B%5Clog+%5Cfrac%7BH_%7BT-t-1%7D+f%28W_%7Bt%2B1%7D%29%7D%7BH_%7BT-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%7D%5Cright%5D+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bt%3D0%7D%5E%7BT-1%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%5Cleft%5BD%28q_t%28W_t%2C+%5Ccdot%29+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+p%28W_t%2C%5Ccdot%29%29%5Cright%5D%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \mathop{\mathbb E}[\log f(W_T)] = \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\log \frac{H_{T-t-1} f(W_{t+1})}{H_{T-t} f(W_t)}\right] = \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \mathop{\mathbb E} \left[D(q_t(W_t, \cdot) \,\|\, p(W_t,\cdot))\right]\,,  "/></p>
<p> where the final inequality uses the definition of <img alt="{q_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bq_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{q_t} "/> in <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqqkernel">(2)</a>. The latter quantity is precisely <img alt="{D(\mu \,\|\, \mu_{\mathcal P})} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%28%5Cmu+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+%5Cmu_%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{D(\mu \,\|\, \mu_{\mathcal P})} "/> by the chain rule for relative entropy.</p>
<p>
<b>Exercise:</b> One should check that if <img alt="{\{A_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BA_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{A_t\}} "/> and <img alt="{\{B_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BB_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{B_t\}} "/> are two time-inhomogeneous Markov chains on <img alt="{\Omega} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\Omega} "/> with respective transition kernels <img alt="{a_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{a_t} "/> and <img alt="{b_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bb_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{b_t} "/> then indeed the chain rule for relative entropy yields <a name="eqchain-ex"/></p><a name="eqchain-ex">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(\{A_0, \ldots, A_T\} \,\|\, \{B_0, \ldots, B_T\}) = \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[D\left(a_t(A_t, \cdot)\,\|\,b_t(A_t,\cdot)\right)\right]\,. \ \ \ \ \ (3) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28%5C%7BA_0%2C+%5Cldots%2C+A_T%5C%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+%5C%7BB_0%2C+%5Cldots%2C+B_T%5C%7D%29+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bt%3D0%7D%5E%7BT-1%7D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Cleft%5BD%5Cleft%28a_t%28A_t%2C+%5Ccdot%29%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2Cb_t%28A_t%2C%5Ccdot%29%5Cright%29%5Cright%5D%5C%2C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%283%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(\{A_0, \ldots, A_T\} \,\|\, \{B_0, \ldots, B_T\}) = \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[D\left(a_t(A_t, \cdot)\,\|\,b_t(A_t,\cdot)\right)\right]\,. \ \ \ \ \ (3) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqchain-ex"/></p>
<p>
We conclude that </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(f \nu_T \,\|\, \nu_T) = D(\mu \,\|\,\mu_{\mathcal P})\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28f+%5Cnu_T+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+%5Cnu_T%29+%3D+D%28%5Cmu+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C%5Cmu_%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%29%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(f \nu_T \,\|\, \nu_T) = D(\mu \,\|\,\mu_{\mathcal P})\,,  "/></p>
<p> and from this one immediately concludes that <img alt="{\mu=\mu^*} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%3D%5Cmu%5E%2A%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu=\mu^*} "/>. Indeed, for any measure <img alt="{\mu' \in \mathcal M_T(f;x_0)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%27+%5Cin+%5Cmathcal+M_T%28f%3Bx_0%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu' \in \mathcal M_T(f;x_0)} "/>, we must have <img alt="{D(\mu' \,\|\,\mu_{\mathcal P}) \geq D(f \nu_T \,\|\,\nu_T)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%28%5Cmu%27+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C%5Cmu_%7B%5Cmathcal+P%7D%29+%5Cgeq+D%28f+%5Cnu_T+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C%5Cnu_T%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{D(\mu' \,\|\,\mu_{\mathcal P}) \geq D(f \nu_T \,\|\,\nu_T)} "/>. This follows because <img alt="{f \nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f \nu_T} "/> is the law of the endpoint of a path drawn from <img alt="{\mu'} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%27%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu'} "/> and <img alt="{\nu_T} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cnu_T%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\nu_T} "/> is the law of the endpoint of a path drawn from <img alt="{\mu} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu} "/>. The relative entropy between the endpoints is certainly less than along the entire path. (This intuitive fact can again be proved via the chain rule for relative entropy by conditioning on the endpoint of the path.)</p>
<p>
</p><p><b>  1.2. The Brownian version </b></p>
<p/><p>
Let us now do the same thing for processes driven by Brownian motion in <img alt="{\mathbb R^n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbb+R%5En%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathbb R^n} "/>. Let <img alt="{\{B_t : t \in [0,1]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BB_t+%3A+t+%5Cin+%5B0%2C1%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{B_t : t \in [0,1]\}} "/> be a Brownian motion with <img alt="{B_0=0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB_0%3D0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{B_0=0} "/>. Let <img alt="{\gamma_n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma_n} "/> be the standard Gaussian measure and recall that <img alt="{B_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{B_1} "/> has law <img alt="{\gamma_n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma_n} "/>.</p>
<p>
We recall that if we have two measures <img alt="{\mu} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu} "/> and <img alt="{\nu} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cnu%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\nu} "/> on <img alt="{\mathbb R^n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbb+R%5En%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathbb R^n} "/> such that <img alt="{\nu} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cnu%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\nu} "/> is absolutely continuous with respect to <img alt="{\mu} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu} "/>, we define the <em>relative entropy</em></p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle D(\nu\,\|\,\mu) = \int d\nu \log \frac{d\nu}{d\mu} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+D%28%5Cnu%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C%5Cmu%29+%3D+%5Cint+d%5Cnu+%5Clog+%5Cfrac%7Bd%5Cnu%7D%7Bd%5Cmu%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle D(\nu\,\|\,\mu) = \int d\nu \log \frac{d\nu}{d\mu} "/></p>
<p>
Our “path space” will consist of drift processes <img alt="{\{W_t : t \in [0,1]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_t+%3A+t+%5Cin+%5B0%2C1%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_t : t \in [0,1]\}} "/> of the form <a name="eqdrift-form"/></p><a name="eqdrift-form">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  W_t = B_t + \int_0^t u_s\,ds\,, \ \ \ \ \ (4) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++W_t+%3D+B_t+%2B+%5Cint_0%5Et+u_s%5C%2Cds%5C%2C%2C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%284%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  W_t = B_t + \int_0^t u_s\,ds\,, \ \ \ \ \ (4) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqdrift-form"/> where <img alt="{\{u_s\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bu_s%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{u_s\}} "/> denotes the drift. We require that <img alt="{\{u_s\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bu_s%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{u_s\}} "/> is progressively measurable, i.e. that the law of <img alt="{u_s} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bu_s%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{u_s} "/> is determined by the past up to time <img alt="{s} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{s} "/>, and that <img alt="{\mathop{\mathbb E} \int_0^1 \|u_s\|^2 \,ds &lt; \infty} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5C%7Cu_s%5C%7C%5E2+%5C%2Cds+%3C+%5Cinfty%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathop{\mathbb E} \int_0^1 \|u_s\|^2 \,ds &lt; \infty} "/>. Note that we can write such a process in differential notation as </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  dW_t = dB_t + u_t\,dt\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++dW_t+%3D+dB_t+%2B+u_t%5C%2Cdt%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  dW_t = dB_t + u_t\,dt\,,  "/></p>
<p> with <img alt="{W_0=0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_0%3D0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_0=0} "/>.</p>
<p>
Fix a smooth density <img alt="{f : \mathbb R^n \rightarrow {\mathbb R}_+} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%3A+%5Cmathbb+R%5En+%5Crightarrow+%7B%5Cmathbb+R%7D_%2B%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f : \mathbb R^n \rightarrow {\mathbb R}_+} "/> with <img alt="{\int f \,d\gamma_n =1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cint+f+%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n+%3D1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\int f \,d\gamma_n =1} "/>.  In analogy with the discrete setting, let us use <img alt="{\mathcal M(f)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal+M%28f%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathcal M(f)} "/> to denote the set of processes <img alt="{\{W_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_t\}} "/> that can be realized in the form <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqdrift-form">(4)</a> and such that <img alt="{W_0 = 0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_0+%3D+0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_0 = 0} "/> and <img alt="{W_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_1} "/> has law <img alt="{f d\gamma_n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+d%5Cgamma_n%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f d\gamma_n} "/>.</p>
<p>
Let us also use the shorthand <img alt="{W_{[0,1]} = \{W_t : t\in [0,1]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%3D+%5C%7BW_t+%3A+t%5Cin+%5B0%2C1%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_{[0,1]} = \{W_t : t\in [0,1]\}} "/> to represent the entire path of the process. Again, we will consider the entropy optimization problem: <a name="eqopt-cont"/></p><a name="eqopt-cont">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \min \left\{ \vphantom{\bigoplus} D\left(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}\right) : W_{[0,1]} \in \mathcal M(f) \right\}\,. \ \ \ \ \ (5) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmin+%5Cleft%5C%7B+%5Cvphantom%7B%5Cbigoplus%7D+D%5Cleft%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%5Cright%29+%3A+W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5Cin+%5Cmathcal+M%28f%29+%5Cright%5C%7D%5C%2C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%285%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \min \left\{ \vphantom{\bigoplus} D\left(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}\right) : W_{[0,1]} \in \mathcal M(f) \right\}\,. \ \ \ \ \ (5) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqopt-cont"/> As in the discrete setting, this problem has a unique optimal solution (in the sense of stochastic processes). Here is the main result.</p>
<blockquote><p><b>Theorem 1 (Föllmer)</b> <em> <a name="thmfollmer"/> If <img alt="{\{ W_t = B_t + \int_0^t u_s\,ds : t \in [0,1]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B+W_t+%3D+B_t+%2B+%5Cint_0%5Et+u_s%5C%2Cds+%3A+t+%5Cin+%5B0%2C1%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{ W_t = B_t + \int_0^t u_s\,ds : t \in [0,1]\}} "/> is the optimal solution to <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqopt-cont">(5)</a>, then </em></p><em>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D\left(W_{[0,1]}\,\|\,B_{[0,1]}\right) = D(W_1 \,\|\, B_1) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|u_t\|^2\,dt\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%5Cleft%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2CB_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%5Cright%29+%3D+D%28W_1+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_1%29+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cu_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D\left(W_{[0,1]}\,\|\,B_{[0,1]}\right) = D(W_1 \,\|\, B_1) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|u_t\|^2\,dt\,.  "/></p>
</em><p><em> </em></p></blockquote>
<p/><p>
Just as for the discrete case, one should think of this as asserting that the optimal process only uses as much entropy as is needed for the difference in laws at the endpoint. The RHS should be thought of as an integral over the expected relative entropy generated at time <img alt="{t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{t} "/> (just as in the chain rule expression <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqchain-ex">(3)</a>).</p>
<p>
The reason for the quadratic term is the usual relative entropy approximation for infinitesimal perturbations. For instance, consider the relative entropy between a binary random variable with expected value <img alt="{\tfrac12 (1-\varepsilon)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctfrac12+%281-%5Cvarepsilon%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\tfrac12 (1-\varepsilon)} "/> and a binary random variable with expected value <img alt="{\tfrac12} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctfrac12%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\tfrac12} "/>: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \frac12(1-\varepsilon) \log (1-\varepsilon) + \frac12 (1+\varepsilon) \log (1+\varepsilon) \approx \frac12 \varepsilon^2\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac12%281-%5Cvarepsilon%29+%5Clog+%281-%5Cvarepsilon%29+%2B+%5Cfrac12+%281%2B%5Cvarepsilon%29+%5Clog+%281%2B%5Cvarepsilon%29+%5Capprox+%5Cfrac12+%5Cvarepsilon%5E2%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \frac12(1-\varepsilon) \log (1-\varepsilon) + \frac12 (1+\varepsilon) \log (1+\varepsilon) \approx \frac12 \varepsilon^2\,.  "/></p>
<p>
I am going to delay the proof of Theorem <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#thmfollmer">1</a> to the next post because doing it in an elementary way will require some discussion of Ito calculus. For now, let us prove the following.</p>
<blockquote><p><b>Lemma 2</b> <em><a name="lemf2"/> For any process <img alt="{W_{[0,1]} \in \mathcal M(f)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5Cin+%5Cmathcal+M%28f%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_{[0,1]} \in \mathcal M(f)} "/> given by a drift <img alt="{\{u_t : t\in[0,1]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bu_t+%3A+t%5Cin%5B0%2C1%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{u_t : t\in[0,1]\}} "/>, it holds that </em></p><em>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(W_1 \,\|\, B_1) \leq D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) =\frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|u_t\|^2\,dt\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28W_1+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_1%29+%5Cleq+D%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%29+%3D%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cu_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(W_1 \,\|\, B_1) \leq D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) =\frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|u_t\|^2\,dt\,.  "/></p>
</em><p><em> </em></p></blockquote>
<p/><p>
<em>Proof:</em>  The proof will be somewhat informal. It can be done easily using <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girsanov_theorem">Girsanov’s theorem</a>, but we try to keep the presentation here elementary and in correspondence with the discrete version above.</p>
<p>
Let us first use the chain rule for relative entropy to calculate <a name="eqchain-rule"/></p><a name="eqchain-rule">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D\left(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\,B_{[0,1]}\right) = \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[D( dW_t \,\|\, dB_t)\right] = \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[D(dB_t + u_t\,dt \,\|\,dB_t)\right]\,. \ \ \ \ \ (6) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%5Cleft%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2CB_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%5Cright%29+%3D+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Cleft%5BD%28+dW_t+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+dB_t%29%5Cright%5D+%3D+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Cleft%5BD%28dB_t+%2B+u_t%5C%2Cdt+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2CdB_t%29%5Cright%5D%5C%2C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%286%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D\left(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\,B_{[0,1]}\right) = \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[D( dW_t \,\|\, dB_t)\right] = \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[D(dB_t + u_t\,dt \,\|\,dB_t)\right]\,. \ \ \ \ \ (6) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqchain-rule"/> Note that <img alt="{dB_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BdB_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dB_t} "/> has the law of a standard <img alt="{n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{n} "/>-dimensional of covariance <img alt="{dt \cdot I} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bdt+%5Ccdot+I%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dt \cdot I} "/>.</p>
<p>
If <img alt="{Z} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BZ%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{Z} "/> is an <img alt="{n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{n} "/>-dimensional Gaussian with covariance <img alt="{\sigma^2 \cdot I} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Csigma%5E2+%5Ccdot+I%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\sigma^2 \cdot I} "/> and <img alt="{u \in \mathbb R^n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bu+%5Cin+%5Cmathbb+R%5En%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{u \in \mathbb R^n} "/>, then </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  D(Z + u \,\|\, Z) &amp;= \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\log \frac{e^{-\|Z\|^2/2\sigma^2}}{e^{-\|u-Z\|^2/2\sigma^2}}\right] \\ &amp;= \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\frac{\|u\|^2}{2\sigma^2} + \frac{\langle u,Z\rangle}{\sigma^2}\right] \\ &amp;= \frac{\|u\|^2}{2\sigma^2}\,. \end{array}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Blll%7D++D%28Z+%2B+u+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+Z%29+%26%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Cleft%5B%5Clog+%5Cfrac%7Be%5E%7B-%5C%7CZ%5C%7C%5E2%2F2%5Csigma%5E2%7D%7D%7Be%5E%7B-%5C%7Cu-Z%5C%7C%5E2%2F2%5Csigma%5E2%7D%7D%5Cright%5D+%5C%5C+%26%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Cleft%5B%5Cfrac%7B%5C%7Cu%5C%7C%5E2%7D%7B2%5Csigma%5E2%7D+%2B+%5Cfrac%7B%5Clangle+u%2CZ%5Crangle%7D%7B%5Csigma%5E2%7D%5Cright%5D+%5C%5C+%26%3D+%5Cfrac%7B%5C%7Cu%5C%7C%5E2%7D%7B2%5Csigma%5E2%7D%5C%2C.+%5Cend%7Barray%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  D(Z + u \,\|\, Z) &amp;= \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\log \frac{e^{-\|Z\|^2/2\sigma^2}}{e^{-\|u-Z\|^2/2\sigma^2}}\right] \\ &amp;= \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\frac{\|u\|^2}{2\sigma^2} + \frac{\langle u,Z\rangle}{\sigma^2}\right] \\ &amp;= \frac{\|u\|^2}{2\sigma^2}\,. \end{array}  "/></p>
<p>
Therefore: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(dB_t + u_t\,dt \,\|\,dB_t) = \mathop{\mathbb E} \left[\frac{\|u_t\|^2 dt^2}{2 dt}\mid \mathcal F_t\right] =\frac12 \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\|u_t\|^2\,dt \mid \mathcal F_t\right]\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28dB_t+%2B+u_t%5C%2Cdt+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2CdB_t%29+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D+%5Cleft%5B%5Cfrac%7B%5C%7Cu_t%5C%7C%5E2+dt%5E2%7D%7B2+dt%7D%5Cmid+%5Cmathcal+F_t%5Cright%5D+%3D%5Cfrac12+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Cleft%5B%5C%7Cu_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt+%5Cmid+%5Cmathcal+F_t%5Cright%5D%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(dB_t + u_t\,dt \,\|\,dB_t) = \mathop{\mathbb E} \left[\frac{\|u_t\|^2 dt^2}{2 dt}\mid \mathcal F_t\right] =\frac12 \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\|u_t\|^2\,dt \mid \mathcal F_t\right]\,,  "/></p>
<p> where the latter expectation is understood to be conditioned on the past <img alt="\mathcal F_t  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cmathcal+F_t++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\mathcal F_t  "/> up to time <img alt="{t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{t} "/>.</p>
<p>
In particular, plugging this into <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqchain-rule">(6)</a>, we have <a name="eqchain2"/></p><a name="eqchain2">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D\left(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\,B_{[0,1]}\right) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|u_t\|^2\,dt\,. \ \ \ \ \ (7) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%5Cleft%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2CB_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%5Cright%29+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cu_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt%5C%2C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%287%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D\left(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\,B_{[0,1]}\right) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|u_t\|^2\,dt\,. \ \ \ \ \ (7) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqchain2"/> <img alt="\Box" class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=eeeeee&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\Box"/></p>
<p>
</p><p><b>  1.3. Brascamp-Lieb </b></p>
<p/><p>
The proof is taken directly from Lehec. We will use the entropic formulation of Brascamp-Lieb due to <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/0710.0870">Carlen and Cordero-Erausquin</a>.</p>
<p>
Let <img alt="{E} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{E} "/> be a Euclidean space with subspaces <img alt="{E_1, E_2, \ldots, E_m} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE_1%2C+E_2%2C+%5Cldots%2C+E_m%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{E_1, E_2, \ldots, E_m} "/>. Let <img alt="{P_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{P_i} "/> denote the orthogonal projection onto <img alt="{E_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{E_i} "/>. Now suppose that for positive numbers <img alt="{c_1, c_2, \ldots, c_m &gt; 0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_1%2C+c_2%2C+%5Cldots%2C+c_m+%3E+0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{c_1, c_2, \ldots, c_m &gt; 0} "/>, we have <a name="eqframe"/></p><a name="eqframe">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \sum_{i=1}^m c_i P_i = \mathrm{id}_E\,. \ \ \ \ \ (8) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5Em+c_i+P_i+%3D+%5Cmathrm%7Bid%7D_E%5C%2C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%288%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \sum_{i=1}^m c_i P_i = \mathrm{id}_E\,. \ \ \ \ \ (8) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqframe"/> By <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqframe">(8)</a>, we have for all <img alt="{x \in E} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx+%5Cin+E%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x \in E} "/>: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle \|x\|^2 = \left\langle x,\sum_{i=1}^m c_i P_i x\right\rangle = \sum_{i=1}^m c_i\|P_i x\|^2\,. " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5C%7Cx%5C%7C%5E2+%3D+%5Cleft%5Clangle+x%2C%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5Em+c_i+P_i+x%5Cright%5Crangle+%3D+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5Em+c_i%5C%7CP_i+x%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2C.+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle \|x\|^2 = \left\langle x,\sum_{i=1}^m c_i P_i x\right\rangle = \sum_{i=1}^m c_i\|P_i x\|^2\,. "/></p>
<p> The latter equality uses the fact that each <img alt="{P_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{P_i} "/> is an orthogonal projection.</p>
<p>
Let <img alt="{Z} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BZ%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{Z} "/> denote a standard Gaussian on <img alt="{E} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{E} "/>, and let <img alt="{Z_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BZ_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{Z_i} "/> denote a standard Gaussian on <img alt="{E_i} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BE_i%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{E_i} "/> for each <img alt="{i=1,2,\ldots, m} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bi%3D1%2C2%2C%5Cldots%2C+m%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{i=1,2,\ldots, m} "/>.</p>
<blockquote><p><b>Theorem 3 (Carlen &amp; Cordero-Erausquin version of Brascamp-Lieb)</b> <em> For any random vector <img alt="{X \in E} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX+%5Cin+E%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{X \in E} "/>, it holds that </em></p><em>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(X \,\|\, Z) \geq \sum_{i=1}^m c_i D(P_i X \,\|\, Z_i)\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28X+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+Z%29+%5Cgeq+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5Em+c_i+D%28P_i+X+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+Z_i%29%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(X \,\|\, Z) \geq \sum_{i=1}^m c_i D(P_i X \,\|\, Z_i)\,.  "/></p>
</em><p><em> </em></p></blockquote>
<p/><p>
<em>Proof:</em>  Let <img alt="{\{W_t : t \in [0,1]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_t+%3A+t+%5Cin+%5B0%2C1%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_t : t \in [0,1]\}} "/> with <img alt="{dW_t = dB_t + v_t\,dt} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BdW_t+%3D+dB_t+%2B+v_t%5C%2Cdt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dW_t = dB_t + v_t\,dt} "/> denote the entropy-optimal drift process such that <img alt="{W_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_1} "/> has the law of <img alt="{X} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BX%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{X} "/>. Then by Theorem <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#thmfollmer">1</a>, </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(X\,\|\,Z) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt = \frac12 \int_0^1 \sum_{i=1}^m c_i \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|P_i v_t\|^2\,dt \geq \sum_{i=1}^m c_i D(P_i X \,\|\, Z_i)\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28X%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2CZ%29+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5Em+c_i+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7CP_i+v_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt+%5Cgeq+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5Em+c_i+D%28P_i+X+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+Z_i%29%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(X\,\|\,Z) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt = \frac12 \int_0^1 \sum_{i=1}^m c_i \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|P_i v_t\|^2\,dt \geq \sum_{i=1}^m c_i D(P_i X \,\|\, Z_i)\,,  "/></p>
<p> where the latter inequality uses Lemma <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#lemf2">2</a> and the fact that <img alt="{P_i W_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_i+W_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{P_i W_1} "/> has law <img alt="{P_i X} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_i+X%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{P_i X} "/>. <img alt="\Box" class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=eeeeee&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\Box"/></p>
<p/></div></content><updated planet:format="November 16, 2015 07:15 AM">2015-11-16T07:15:04Z</updated><published planet:format="November 16, 2015 07:15 AM">2015-11-16T07:15:04Z</published><category term="Expository"/><category term="Math"/><category term="Brascamp-Lieb"/><category term="Brownian motion"/><category term="entropy maximization"/><category term="Follmer drift"/><category term="Ito calculus"/><author><name>James</name></author><source><id>https://tcsmath.wordpress.com</id><logo>https://s0.wp.com/i/buttonw-com.png</logo><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/osd.xml" rel="search" type="application/opensearchdescription+xml"/><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/?pushpress=hub" rel="hub" type="text/html"/><subtitle>some mathematics &amp; computation</subtitle><title>tcs math</title><updated planet:format="December 17, 2018 05:29 AM">2018-12-17T05:29:01Z</updated><planet:module>toc</planet:module><planet:format>atom10</planet:format><planet:http_last_modified>Fri, 13 Apr 2018 03:53:48 GMT</planet:http_last_modified><planet:bozo>false</planet:bozo><planet:items_per_page>40</planet:items_per_page><planet:css-id>tcs-math</planet:css-id><planet:face>jrl.jpeg</planet:face><planet:name>tcs math</planet:name><planet:http_location>https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/</planet:http_location><planet:http_status>301</planet:http_status></source></entry>
